{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>In the previous section we saw usage of withScope HOC. This section is all\nabout what scopes are and how to take benefits from them.</p>\n<h2 id=\"what-a-scope-is\"><a href=\"#what-a-scope-is\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What a Scope is?</h2>\n<p>Scope is a barrier for parts of our application: components, states,\nreducers, actions and sagas. In k-frame Each reusable component has its own\nscope. It means it is fully independent, and you can reuse it wherever you\nneed to.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"rules-of-scope\"><a href=\"#rules-of-scope\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Rules of Scope</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>It canâ€™t access any information from the ancestor scopes, until that\ninformation are directly passed</li>\n<li>It can contain sub scopes</li>\n<li>It can access information stored sub scopes.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"why-scopes-are-important\"><a href=\"#why-scopes-are-important\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Why Scopes are important?</h2>","frontmatter":{"title":"Introducing Scopes","next":"introducing-jsx.html","prev":"counter.html"},"fields":{"path":"content/docs/introducing-scopes.md","slug":"docs/introducing-scopes.html"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"docs/introducing-scopes.html"}}